<ns4842:section xmlns:ns4842="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.lang.arrays.declaringArrayReferences">
  <ns4843:title xmlns:ns4843="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Declaring an Array Reference</ns4843:title>
  <ns4844:para xmlns:ns4844="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    Since arrays are first class objects, one accesses them like other objects via references.
  </ns4844:para>
  <ns4845:para xmlns:ns4845="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    An reference is types in Java, i.e. you declare an array refernce of some type which
    is either a primitive data type or a class. To specify that the reference is a reference
    to an array of the specified data type, one adds a pair of square brackets after the the
    data type. For example, below we declare a reference which can point to any array of
    <ns4846:literal xmlns:ns4846="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">double</ns4846:literal>s:
    <ns4847:programlisting xmlns:ns4847="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
double[] vec;
    </ns4847:programlisting>
  </ns4845:para>
  <ns4848:para xmlns:ns4848="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    In a similar way we can define a reference to an array of accounts:
    <ns4849:programlisting xmlns:ns4849="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
Account[] accounts;
    </ns4849:programlisting>
  </ns4848:para>
</ns4842:section>